===Noun===
{{en-noun|kerfs}}

# The [[groove]] or [[slit]] created by cutting a workpiece; an [[incision]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1999|passage=They pass through a cleft that has been made across a low range of hills, like a '''kerf''' in the top of a log, and enter into a lovely territory of subtly swelling emerald green fields strewn randomly with small white capsules that he takes to be sheep.|author=[[w:Neal Stephenson|Neal Stephenson]]|title=Cryptonomicon}}
# The width of the groove made while cutting with a saw or [[w:Laser cutting|laser]].
#* '''1991''', [[w:Popular Mechanics|Popular Mechanics]], January issue, [http://books.google.ru/books?id=feMDAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA63&ots=5KtnX0zrbr&dq=kerf&pg=PA63#v=onepage&q=kerf&f=false page 63], "Thin-kerf blades", by Rosario Capotostro
#*: Sawing with a thin-kerf blade produces a '''kerf''' that's 1/2 to 1/3 the size of a standard blade '''kerf'''.
# The distance between [[diverge|diverging]] [[saw]] [[teeth]].
# The portion of [[hay]], [[turf]], [[wool]], etc. yielded by a single [[cut]] or [[shear]]ing stroke.

